burgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Skotland, United Kingdom","Preston, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1226–1296":"1226–1296","1228–1296":"1228–1296","1230–Male":"1230–Overleden","1230–Female":"1230–Overleden","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1190–1260":"1190–1260","about 1260":"circa 1260","1190":"1190","1228":"1228","1226":"1226","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1260":"1260","1329":"1329","Westmoreland, England":"Westmorland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Preston, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1226–1296":"1226–1296","1228–1296":"1228–1296","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1190–1260":"1190–1260","about 1260":"about 1260","1190":"1190","1228":"1228","1226":"1226","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1251":"1251","1260":"1260","1329":"1329","Westmoreland, England":"Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom","Preston, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Preston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from one of the many places (most notably one in Lancashire) so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","occasionally from Middle English <i>prest</i> + <i>son</i> ‘son of the priest’. Priests were forbidden marriage but many produced illegitimate offspring."],"variants":[{"name":"Presson","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): variant of   Preston  .","French: occupational name for a presser of wine or oil, from a derivative of <i>presser</i> ‘to press’."]},{"name":"Prestwich","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire (now Greater Manchester), so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying settlement’, or from other places with the same derivation. Variants such as <i>Prestidge</i>, <i>Prestage</i>, etc., parallel the local pronunciation of the Lancashire name. Compare   Preston  ."]}]},{"name":"Baron","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the title of nobility, along the lines of   Earl   and   Duke .  The title arose in the Norman feudal system and seems to be of Germanic origin, derived from Old English <i>beorn</i> ‘young warrior’ or a related continental Germanic form. In part the given name, and in particular the variant  <b>Barron</b> , may represent the surname derived from the title."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Baron William Preston was born in 1226, in Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Leolphus de Preston. He married Sybil Ross in 1251, in Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1296, in Westmorland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1226–1296":"1226–1296","1228–1296":"1228–1296","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud"